'''Nashitomi no Mikoto''' (梨迹臣命, birth and death dates unknown) was an ancient Japanese noble and ancestor of the {{ill|Nakatomi clan|ja|中臣氏|12=draft|12=draft}}. He is also known by the names Nashifu no Mikoto, Nashitsu no Mikoto, and Nashitomi.
== Overview == Although Nashitomi no Mikoto does not appear in the *{{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|12=draft|12=draft}}* or *{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft|12=draft}}*, he is mentioned in the *{{ill|Ōmi no Kuni Fudoki|ja|近江国風土記|12=draft|12=draft}}*. According to the text, he was the second son of {{ill|Igatsuomi no Mikoto|ja|伊賀津臣命|12=draft|12=draft}}, who had two sons and two daughters with a celestial maiden in the {{ill|Hagoromo|ja|羽衣伝説|12=draft|12=draft}} associated with {{ill|Lake Yogo|ja|余呉湖|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Ōmi Province|ja|近江国|12=draft|12=draft}}, Ikagō District.<ref name="fudoki">Yoshirō Akimoto, *Nihon Koten Bungaku Taikei Shinsōban Fudoki* (Iwanami Shoten, 1993), pp. 457-458.</ref>
Nashitomi no Mikoto is enshrined as a deity at the *{{ill|Omi Shrine (Yogo)|lt=Noimi Shrine|ja|乃彌神社|12=draft|12=draft}}*, a {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|12=draft|12=draft}} in Ōmi Province, where he is worshipped alongside his brother Omishiru no Mikoto at the *{{ill|lt=Omi Shrine|Omi Shrine (Yogo)|ja|乎彌神社|12=draft|12=draft}}*, which incorporated Noimi Shrine. Additionally, he is also enshrined at *{{ill|Ōfura Shrine|ja|意富布良神社|12=draft|12=draft}}* as a subordinate deity.
== Genealogy == Nashitomi no Mikoto was the son of {{ill|Igatsuomi no Mikoto|ja|伊賀津臣命|12=draft|12=draft}} and father of {{ill|Kamikikikatsu|lt=Kamikikikatsu no Mikoto|ja|神聞勝命|12=draft|12=draft}}. His descendants include prominent clans such as the {{ill|Nakatomi clan|ja|中臣氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ōnakatomi clan|ja|大中臣氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Fujiwara clan|ja|藤原氏|12=draft|12=draft}}.
The *{{ill|Shinsen Shōjiroku|ja|新撰姓氏録|1=Shinsen Shōjiroku|12=draft|12=draft}}* identifies him as the ancestor of the Kawamatauji no Muraji of {{ill|Kawachi Province|ja|河内国|12=draft|12=draft}}.
